05357nam a22007335i 9780812201321DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20142008pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122013217 a10.9783/97808122013212doi  a(DE-B1597)451004  a(OCoLC)979576048  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHD7288.78.U52bN726 2008eb 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a363.5/850974712221 aBloom, Nicholas Dagen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPublic Housing That Worked :bNew York in the Twentieth Century /cNicholas Dagen Bloom. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b33 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Model Housing as a Municipal Service -- tChapter 1. Defining a Housing Crisis -- tChapter 2. Three Programs Are Better Than One -- tChapter 3. High-Rise Public Housing Begins -- tChapter 4. Model Tenants for Model Housing -- tChapter 5. Tightly Managed Communities -- tPart II: Transforming Postwar New York -- tChapter 6. The Boom Years -- tChapter 7. Designs for a New Metropolis -- tChapter 8. The Price of Design Reform -- tChapter 9. The Benefits of Social Engineering -- tChapter 10. Meeting the Management Challenge -- tPart III: Welfare-State Public Housing -- tChapter 11. Surviving the Welfare State -- tChapter 12. The Value of Consistency -- tPart IV: Affordable Housing -- tChapter 13. Model Housing Revisited -- tAppendix A: Guide to Housing Developments -- tAppendix B: Tenant Selection Policies and Procedures -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen it comes to large-scale public housing in the United States, the consensus for the past decades has been to let the wrecking balls fly. The demolition of infamous projects, such as Pruitt-Igoe in St. Louis and the towers of Cabrini-Green in Chicago, represents to most Americans the fate of all public housing. Yet one notable exception to this national tragedy remains. The New York City Housing Authority, America's largest public housing manager, still maintains over 400,000 tenants in its vast and well-run high-rise projects. While by no means utopian, New York City's public housing remains an acceptable and affordable option.The story of New York's success where so many other housing authorities faltered has been ignored for too long. Public Housing That Worked shows how New York's administrators, beginning in the 1930s, developed a rigorous system of public housing management that weathered a variety of social and political challenges. A key element in the long-term viability of New York's public housing has been the constant search for better methods in fields such as tenant selection, policing, renovation, community affairs, and landscape design.Nicholas Dagen Bloom presents the achievements that contradict the common wisdom that public housing projects are inherently unmanageable. By focusing on what worked, rather than on the conventional history of failure and blame, Bloom provides useful models for addressing the current crisis in affordable urban housing. Public Housing That Worked is essential reading for practitioners and scholars in the areas of public policy, urban history, planning, criminal justice, affordable housing management, social work, and urban affairs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCity planningzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic housingzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 4aAmerican Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aPolitical Science.  aP